---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Portrait from '../../components/Portrait.astro';
---
<Base title="About — Dr. Lior Tabansky" description="Dr. Lior Tabansky works where defense innovation, AI, and digital trust meet — turning deep expertise into decisions governments and investors can act on." lang="en" dir="ltr">
  <div class="page page--about">
    <header class="page-section page-header">
      <div class="site-container page-header__layout">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
          <h1>Strategy that survives contact with reality.</h1>
        </div>
        <div class="page-header__aside">
          <Portrait variant="square" alt="Dr. Lior Tabansky" />
          <p class="subhead">I work at the meeting point of defense innovation, artificial intelligence, and digital trust — for governments and investors who need judgment they can act on, not another report.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="page-section narrative-section" aria-labelledby="through-line-title">
      <div class="site-container prose-layout">
        <header class="section-heading"><p class="eyebrow">The through-line</p><h2 id="through-line-title">Operational grounding, strategic application.</h2></header>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>My grounding is operational. I served in an elite Israel Air Force technology unit built around a major innovation for multi-domain warfare — where I learned that advantage comes from how technology meets organization, not from the technology alone. That question has driven my work since.</p>
          <p>I built the argument into a theory of cyber-power — presented at NATO's Cooperative Cyber Defence Centre of Excellence and set out in <cite>Cybersecurity in Israel</cite> (Springer), written with Major General Isaac Ben-Israel. Then I put it to work. As Director of Strategy on an advisory to the Government of Singapore, I authored the vision, goals, and 70+ recommendations behind the country's National Cybersecurity Strategy. In World Bank–backed work, I led critical-infrastructure resilience roadmaps across a dozen countries in Europe, Asia, and Africa, and turned a Tel Aviv University research practice into a self-funding professional-services unit.</p>
          <p>The through-line is commercial as much as strategic. I've designed executive programs that closed the gap between boards and cyber risk, and I advise investors and governments on where defense and AI innovation actually creates value — and where it only looks like it does.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="page-section method-section" aria-labelledby="method-title">
      <div class="site-container prose-layout">
        <header class="section-heading"><p class="eyebrow">How I work</p><h2 id="method-title">From first principles.</h2></header>
        <div class="prose prose--feature">
          <p>When the playbooks don't fit — and at the frontier they rarely do — I reason from first principles. I map the whole system, separate signal from noise, and, as Michael Porter put it, decide what not to do. To do that rigorously, I developed a method to analyze an entire sector as a complex socio-technical-economic system, drawing on complexity science, network science, public policy, and safety engineering.</p>
          <p>It's also why I'm wary of frontier-model theater. AI already delivers insight, decision support, and autonomy. The challenge is no longer whether the capability exists, but whether organizations can use it: successful adoption is an organizational problem, not a model problem.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="page-section engagements-section" aria-labelledby="about-engagements-title">
      <div class="site-container section-grid">
        <header class="section-heading"><p class="eyebrow">Selected engagements</p><h2 id="about-engagements-title">Work made public selectively.</h2></header>
        <p class="feature-copy">Public anchors: Singapore's National Cybersecurity Strategy and capacity work with the World Bank. Most of what I do is private — for governments and investors who value discretion.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="page-section credentials-section" aria-labelledby="credentials-title">
      <div class="site-container section-grid">
        <header class="section-heading"><p class="eyebrow">Credentials</p><h2 id="credentials-title">Selected foundations.</h2></header>
        <ul class="record-list">
          <li>PhD, Tel Aviv University — a strategic-adaptation framework for national cybersecurity, comparing Singapore, Israel, and the United States.</li>
          <li>Adjunct Associate Professor, Coller School of Management, teaching cyber risk to business leaders.</li>
          <li>Author, <cite>Cybersecurity in Israel</cite> (Springer, with Maj. Gen. Isaac Ben-Israel).</li>
          <li>Selected work: NATO CCDCOE (CyCon) · <cite>IEEE Engineering Management Review</cite> · <cite>The National Interest</cite>.</li>
          <li>Shared platforms with Joseph Nye and Martin Libicki. English, Russian, and Hebrew — natively.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="page-section inquiry-section" aria-labelledby="about-inquiry-title">
      <div class="site-container inquiry-layout">
        <h2 id="about-inquiry-title">For advisory, investment, or media inquiries.</h2>
        <a class="text-link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ltaba/">Private inquiries <span class="directional-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
